rgan of Cydweli1岁，母亲Joan-2岁。他和Mes. Llywelyn sap LLywelyn至少有1个女儿。"},"hr":{"about 1075–":"oko 1075.–preminuo","1075–Male":"1075–preminuo","1104–Male":"1104–preminuo","–Male":"preminuo","1080–Female":"1080–preminula","1110–Female":"1110–preminula","1078–Female":"1078–preminula","1080":"1080","1104":"1104","1078":"1078","1110":"1110","1075":"1075","about 1110":"oko 1110.","about 1075":"oko 1075.","Wales":"Wales"},"cs":{"about 1075–":"okolo 1075–Zesnulý","1075–Male":"1075–Zesnulý","1104–Male":"1104–Zesnulý","–Male":"Zesnulý","1080–Female":"1080–Zesnulá","1110–Female":"1110–Zesnulá","1078–Female":"1078–Zesnulá","1080":"1080","1104":"1104","1078":"1078","1110":"1110","1075":"1075","about 1110":"okolo 1110","about 1075":"okolo 1075","Wales":"Wales"},"da":{"about 1075–":"omkring 1075–Afdød","1075–Male":"1075–Afdød","1104–Male":"1104–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1080–Female":"1080–Afdød","1110–Female":"1110–Afdød","1078–Female":"1078–Afdød","1080":"1080","1104":"1104","1078":"1078","1110":"1110","1075":"1075","about 1110":"omkring 1110","about 1075":"omkring 1075","Wales":"Wales"},"nl":{"about 1075–":"circa 1075–Overleden","1075–Male":"1075–Overleden","1104–Male":"1104–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1080–Female":"1080–Overleden","1110–Female":"1110–Overleden","1078–Female":"1078–Overleden","1080":"1080","1104":"1104","1078":"1078","1110":"1110","1075":"1075","about 1110":"circa 1110","about 1075":"circa 1075","Wales":"Wales"},"en":{"about 1075–":"about 1075–Deceased","1075–Male":"1075–Deceased","1104–Male":"1104–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1110–Female":"1110–Deceased","1078–Female":"1078–Deceased","1080":"1080","1104":"1104","1078":"1078","1110":"1110","1075":"1075","about 1110":"about 1110","about 1075":"about 1075","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"LLywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llywelyn ap LLywelyn was born about 1075, in Wales, his father, Llewelyn ap Gwrgan of Cydweli, was 1 and his mother, Joan, was -2. He had at least 1 daughter with Mes. Llywelyn sap LLywelyn."},"et":{"about 1075–":"umbes 1075–Surnud","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1104–Male":"1104–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1078–Female":"1078–Surnud","1080":"1080","1104":"1104","1078":"1078","1110":"1110","1075":"1075","about 1110":"umbes 1110","about 1075":"umbes 1075","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"abou